ans to learn about the world, granting sentient animals the capacity to model, predict, and simulate. Mitchell reveals how these faculties reached their peak in humans with our abilities to imagine and to be introspective, to reason in the moment, and to shape our possible futures through the exercise of our individual agency. Mitchell’s argument has important implications—for how we understand decision making, for how our individual agency can be enhanced or infringed, for how we think about collective agency in the face of global crises, and for how we consider the limitations and future of artificial intelligence.An astonishing journey of discovery, Free Agents offers a new framework for understanding how, across a billion years of Earth history, life evolved the power to choose, and why it matters.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBrainxEvolution. 0aEvolutionary psychology. 0aFree will and determinismxPhysiological aspects. 0aNeurosciences. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Neuroscience.2bisacsh  aAgency.  aFree Agents: How Evolution Created the Power to Choose.  aKevin Mitchell.  aPrinceton : evolution choice.  aPrinceton University Press.  aaction.  aartificial intelligence.  abehavior.  abehavioral control.  abrain.  acausation.  acharacter.  achoice.  acognition.  acognitive science.  acompatibilism.  aconsciousness.  adecision-making.  adeterminism.  adualism.  aevolution.  afree will.  afreedom.  agenetics.  agoal-oriented behavior.  ahabits.  aindeterminacy.  ainnate traits.  ameaning.  amental causation.  amind.  amoral responsibility.  aneuroscience.  aorigin of life.  aperception.  apersonality.  aphilosophy.  aphysics.  apredispositions.  apsychology.  apurpose.  aquantum physics.  areason.  areductionism.  aself